title: Owl statue with Voronoi style cavity

description.text:
Owl statue remix, inspired by another remix by Guidoo. I wanted more of the details from the original statue, and I wanted the Voroni style "cage" cavity to cover the inside wall aswell as be more smooth and thick. I plan on pausing it about half way through, and adding a shiny coin in the cage - just for fun.
A marble could also be great - or maybe a pre-printed egg. New: I added a low-poly version of the model, in case the full version is too much.
Obviously some details are lost in the low version, but it's still great - it's mainly the cage-part that has had it's polygon count lowered - most of the owl itself is identical.

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Doesn't Matter

Notes: Should print without support, though there are some tricky overhangs in the cage.

First I loaded the original statue stl into meshmixer, and smoothed out the chest.
Partly since I prefer that look, but mainly since I wanted to import in into TinkerCAD to add the chest cage there (and TinkerCAD doesn't support more than 300.000 polygons in imported models). After importing it in TinkerCAD, I carved out the hole in the chest, and modified a Voroni sphere to fit my needs, and finally joined everything together. This left the cage rather crudely connected to the statue, so I ended up using quite a few hours in MeshMixer to smooth everything out and make it join the owl nicer. After my first test print, I realized that the cage was too thin, and unprintable, so I spent a few more hours in MeshMixer making the cage "bars" thicker. And now I think it's just about perfect :-)

description.text: This week I've been working with the Institution of Mechanical Engineers and Bloodhound SSC with balloon powered cars at a Tomorrow's Engineer's event. It inspired me to add "rocket", or rather, Balloon Power to the ThinkFun kit. It's simply the small connector with an added pipe - getting to know the sizes of ThinkFun parts I'm probably going to revise this to give ground clearance if medium wheel are attached directly. The shape of the original part doesn't lend itself to "edge" printing, you'll see a defect in the print - that's a simple tweak in the update (to follow). The Balloon can be inflated by blowing through the pipe, nipping the neck of the balloon between puffs. If you're mounting this inside a box chassis you can use the pipe extension to get your "jet" nozzle outside the box. Update #1 - New pictures, reduced nozzle to give ground clearance with Medium Wheels - STLs to follow, minor tweak required to remove model glitch. Still thinking about balloon to nozzle transition too. Update #2 - New Files and Picture. Slight hiccup on print lifting/deformation but otherwise good. Still thinking and Balloon Car assembly to follow. Update #3 - Mk2 extension removed pending update to resolve wall thickness. Note original extension is NOT compatible with Mk2 Pipe. Still playing with boxes, wheels MUST be free running if you're going to get the best out of the thrust available. Larger bore of the original is better in this instance but doubling up Balloons (one inside the other) can help force the air out for greater thrust too ;) Update #4 - simple test: https://vimeo.com/145046225

Most of the parts are from Josef Prusa's Prusa3-vanilla: https://github.com/josefprusa/Prusa3-vanilla/tree/master However x-carriage of 30mm has been used and compact extruder has been adapted accordingly. Subtle changes for adapting nut traps have been done to some parts too. You can get the parts from our fifth edition too:
https://www.youmagine.com/designs/fifth-prusa-i3-workshop-in-valencia

Please note this parts were created for T2.5 belts (x-carriage and y-beltholder). You can use our on-line animated building guide: http://www.carlos-sanchez.com/Prusa3 or the Linux binary http://www.carlos-sanchez.com/Prusa3/Linux.zip

Nothing really to print here. Just an idea to dry out your filament. Wet filament deposits water in the hot end of your printer. The water turns to steam and causes the hot plastic to spurt out of the nozzle leaving a glob on the side of your print. I've been looking for a way to dry out my filament. I store it in plastic bags with a desiccant but sometimes that isn't enough. I live in a fairly humid region and I have a lot of problems with wet filament. My wife won't let me use her brand new stove to dry out my filament so I had to improvise. The idea was to go to a second hand store and purchase a dehydrator. I found one for really cheap. I had some left over plastic sheet so I wrapped it around the base and top of the dehydrator. It will dry three rolls of filament in about 2 hours. Instead of a plastic sheet you might be able to use a piece of poster board covered with shipping tape. I would like to hear about other ways makers dry out their filament. Cheers.

Links to pop together to make a chain for a bracelet or necklace. Two lengths of link provided and a twist-action clasp. This clasp is a bit stiff and there's no tactile feedback to help identify the links, but it works.

Printed at both standard (0.2mm layer height) and high quality (0.1mm layer height). Standard quality has worked tolerably well. To assemble put one on a solid surface and press another down from above. I have actually taken to using a hammer* to pound a one piece onto another. Tolerances are close and the amount of expansion in a print depends on the plastic. Earlier prints I had fairly low survival rates for pieces, but after printer repairs things are much better. Out of ~40 links this morning one piece misprinted and one broke during assembly. The pay off for the close tolerances and difficulty assembly is a durable chain that takes considerable force to break. If a link breaks during assembly use pliers to put a 90 degree or more bend at one end of a straightened paper clip. Hook this into hole of the ball and use pliers to keep a good grip on the paper clip and pull it out. If the other half of the broken link is already part of a chain use pliers to pull it off making sure to grip it at the end so as not to damage the head of the link snapped into it.
  • not literally a hammer. I frequently disassemble hard drives and actually what I use are empty aluminum drive housings that are lying around.

This is a better hood ornament clone than others on thingiverse, but still not the best. This is one of my first models, so please don't expect it to be that great. I couldn't find a good Mercedes hood ornament without supports that I could sit on my desk, look 3D printed, but still similar to the real thing. The tolerances between the parts were small, so sanding may be required and glue is not necessary to keep them together. This was very simple to make, it only took five minutes. You can fit it together and keep it as-is, or paint it silver. You can find how I made it in the other section.

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2 mm

Infill:

30%

Notes: Printed in silver ABS with heated bed at 90C on Da Vinci 1.0A. Warping occurred at any bed temperature under 90. Sliced with Slic3r and g-code hosted by R-H (Repetier-Host).
Just used sandpaper to lightly sand inside hole of the base. You can also acetone-smooth (if using ABS) or spray paint it silver.

You can use this process to make almost any 3D model from a .png image. To make it, I found and cropped an image of the mercedes logo from Google. I removed the background and made it transparent in Preview on my Mac. I then converted the file to a .svg and imported it into Tinkercad. I made it thicker, added the connection cylinder, and created the base with a half-sphere with a hole just bigger than the connector on the logo part. After, I smoothed both parts in blender. I imported into R-H and printed both parts in one print on my Da Vinci 1.0A and slid the parts together after light sanding. Find my recommended print settings in instructions tab.

This is a very tight tolerance concentric ring fit and calibration test. It was designed around PLA but should be applicable to any material. It is assumed that the printer on which the test is run can hold a tolerance of 0.1 mm. It is highly recommended that the basic filament calibration test found here http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1037301 be run before you try this one. This calibration and fit test consists of three rings that match up and fit inside each other to test different parameters. This will test the fit between two walls, the fit inside a single wall, and flushness on the inner walls from one part to the next. If your X or Y axis are not calibrated properly you will print an oval which will not allow the parts to fit properly. This will also test short span 4 mm radial bridges. If you are getting any sag in any direction the middle ring will not fit flush. Once printed the only post processing that might need to be done is first removing the lip sometimes created around the edges on the first layer from the squish needed to stick it to the bed. Second, removal of the small vertical ridge sometimes created where a the head starts and stops on a ring and retraction is not quite tuned right. There should be no need to touch any of the other surfaces. When assembled the tolerances will be very tight at around 0.10 - 0.15 mm clearance and the three parts will look like one. The pictures show the sequence for putting the parts together and the final assembly orientation. It's fun to show this assembled print to people and ask it they can figure out how you printed it without supports. The STL file includes all three parts as a collection. They are CURA scaled and oriented for printing.

A friend at work had an old drawer with a broken runner wheel. The manufacturer no longer makes them. What a perfect situation for a 3D printer! I modeled the existing wheel in Autodesk's 123D Design using nothing but cylinders of various sizes, using the Combine/Merge and Combine/Subtract tools. I chamfered the edges of the wheel, but realized after printing the first prototype it wasn't enough, so added more and the second prototype looked good. I added the screw pocket on one side so when screwed to the bracket, the head will have some recessed room to hide in. 
The wheel measures 28.2mm in diameter, with a 7mm hole in the center. The projection on the side is 5.26mm. I'm including the 123D file in case anyone else needs to modify this to suit their application.

description.text: These files are a remix of jasonm621's "Printable Marble Machine #1" and Alzibiff's "Motorised Marble Machine" files. I modified the base of the motorised marble machine to accommodate a "AA" battery holder and a toggle switch as seen in the photos (inspired by dmassey's "Battery Base" remix). I also modified the remixed motor mount made by Dogbert to hold the Pololu 298:1 micro gear motor (Cat #3069) without using the optional Pololu motor bracket. The battery holder can be sourced on eBay using the search words "4 X AA Battery Holder" and the switch I used can be found using the words "Mini Toggle Switch". I secured the battery holder to the battery base using two small screws and the motor just pushes into the motor mount for a snug fit (as seen in the photos). I also modified the "Helix Holder" file to remove the hole for the power plug and added a few new holes just for fun. Please visit Alzibiff's Thingiverse page for the other files and instructions needed to print the Motorized Marble Machine. Thanks to all of the makers that helped to inspire this design and thanks for looking at my contribution to Thingiverse!!!

description.text:
Perhaps the smallest and cheapest rover you can print.
The stepper motors are 4 Wire 2 Phase Mimi stepper motor micro stepper motor D6xH11mm with small Copper gear: http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00M7QQIZ6?
Found this datasheet online: http://www.nidec-copal-electronics.com/e/product/files/file/b862724e290bcc90376e42235e959fd090c36ad7.pdf
Seems it can pull around 300mA for 3N so try to get better batteries that what I have. I suggest two 3.7V 680mAh lipo batteries tied in series to the Raw pin on the arduino. Here's what I plan on upgrading to: https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00MF3SAF2/ref=ox_sc_act_title_1?ie=UTF8&psc=1&smid=A3EFY0HU0G8BT6 The controller is Estone New Version Pro Mini Module Atmega328 5v 16m for Arduino Compatible: http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00GLES8BW? After the 8 DIO required for the steppers, you are left with 6 DIO and 8 AIO for any sensing you want to add to it. Keep the batteries light since the steppers cannot handle too much weight. Enjoy UPDATE: I made the wheels much smaller (less required torque on the motors) and added battery holders. I'm using 3.7V 110mAh batteries from a quadrotor toy (only need one battery for a long run). Let me know if you have questions.

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.1 mm

Infill:

100%

Notes: As this print is tiny, obviously print at 100% and as fine a resolution as possible and very slow. It won't take 10 minutes to print anyway. With the wheels, print as is and gently widen the whole with a drill bit until they can wedge onto the stepper gear - be gentle though because you can pop the gear through the stepper case (ruining it). I broke 3 steppers doing this.

Step 1: Solder wire leads to steppers (sorry for picture). Be careful as the stepper pins can burn/pull off. Step 2: Snap in stepper motors (should be a tight fit - don't snap plastic support). Also don't push directly on the gears since they can push through - ruining the stepper. I pre-snip and tin the wires to make soldering in the arduino easier. The stepper coil pin pairs are perpendicular to the stepper shaft. Wire accordingly (can fix in code later anyway). Step 3: Solder Arduino to motors. I used DIO 6-9 for the left motor, and 13-10 for the right motor. Step 4: Don't do what I did and hot glue the pcb to the chassis... makes soldering the header pins a pain in the a$$. Step 5: wiggle on wheels (will need some fine tuning with a drill bit but don't push too hard on the gears), slap in one or two batteries, and you're ready to code.

AccelStepper.h In order to run multiple stepper motors simultaneously, check out AccelStepper library on GitHub. It's simple, lean, and super easy to use. Here's where you can get it:
https://github.com/adafruit/AccelStepper Arduino Starter Code // MultiStepper.pde

This is an OpenSCAD script providing several modules for generating linear motion flexures(also sometimes referred to as translational compliant mechanism).
These are parts that are designed to flex in such a way that permits motion only along one axis, while being relatively stiff to off-axis movement. They are often used for applications such as precise optical positioning, and when constructed of stable materials(not printed plastic) can be made to operate with nanoscale precision. They can be used for small scale linear motion. Some advantages of flexures over typical slides are:
  • zero backlash
  • zero wear
  • zero friction/stiction
  • can be easily fabricated from single block of material using subtractive mfg. (waterjet, laser cutter, cnc mill, router, EDM, etc)
  • linear motion using only 1 part
    • The patterns in this script were mainly inspired by images and videos found online showing various linear flexures, typically composed from metall or even galss. I tried to incorporate nearly every general pattern I found for single axis motion. The flexure modules generate a 2d profile of the slots that should be cut out of your part.
    Parameters used in generating the profiles are:
    shuttleSize: [x,y] dimensions of the inner piece which moves
    slotWidth: Width of slots which are cut from the part, determines max travel
    beamLength: The beams are the parts which are designed to flex. Longer beams may be necessary for stiffer materials.
    minWidth: The beams can be notched down to provide more flexible pivot points on the ends, this is the minimum they will be notched down to.
    maxWidth: This is the width of the beams in all places where not notched. If minWidth equals maxWidth, there will be no notches. Both minWidth and maxWidth should probably be a multiple of your nozzle diameter.
    notchScale When maxWidth is only slightly larger than minWidth, the notch will be a very tiny semicircle. Notch scale stretches this circle wider to a more reasonable feature size, without affecting the minWidth of the beam
    centerSize: This is the distance between the left and right beams Only used with symmetric designs. It should be greater than or equal to maxWidth for strength. Also less than or equal to shuttleSize X dimension. If set equal to shuttleX, the beams will be placed on the side of the shuttle and the overall pattern is vertically shorter. The provided STLs and Customizer are available as examples of the various configurations possible using this script, but for real applications you will likely want to specify your own bolt holes for anchoring the part, and means of adjusting the position.
    For an example application see my Z-Probe Mount here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1119715
    Another idea is to use a printed flexure as a spring for a vehicle suspension, or maybe vibration isolation feet for a printer. Some flexures in the wild are multistage, providing x and y motion for example. I have not experimented with this, but it should be possible to nest a single axis flexure inside another(rotated 90degrees) to provide 2 axis motion.

Here are some handy scripts you can build as .s3g files to put on your Thing-O-Matic's SD card to call up on your Gen4 Interface kit (http://store.makerbot.com/makerbot-interface-board-kit-v1-1.html). These simple utility scripts are in use in the MakerBot BotFarm on a row of Thing-O-Matics with Stepstruder MK6-Plus 3mm toolheads, each calibrated the same way. By taking a look at the start.gcode and end.gcode of your MK5 or MK6 1.75mm toolheads you can make adjustments to these scripts for a broader range of machines.

TOMcalib:
This script is a stripped down version of the RepG 25 Calibration script. Before running the script you center the platform to the nozzle on the XY axes and then lower the nozzle to touch flat to the build platform without pressing into it. Select the TOMcalib script using the Interface kit and activate it. The z-platform will raise up to touch the Z-max endstop and the platform will move to the right and back to touch the x- and y-min endstops. The travel from the centered positions overwrites the Motherboard x/y/z offset values so that when a RepG 25 or later print runs, the proper build envelop information will be in place. To use this script best, have a handy object like a hollow calibration cube or similar to run immediately after running this script. While it is easy to open up Machines > Motherboard Onboard Preferences to make manually adjustments to the z-height (in particular), it is better to get a feel for the right placement of the nozzle before running the calibration script each time so that you can adjust your MakerBot in the field without issue. TOMextrude50:
This script heats up the toolhead to 225 degrees celsius and extrudes for 50s. You can tune to run this longer by changing the value of the milliseconds assigned in the G04 command -- one second equals 1000 milliseconds. Great tool to heat up to change filaments or exporting a little filler for a void on a model. TOMconvey50:
This script advances the conveyor belt for an ABP for 50 seconds. Great for advancing the belt to a better section or testing to make sure that the DC motor power is correctly routed. You can always cancel out of this quickly if you just want to quickly check belt direction! TOMextruder120:
2min of extrusion is better for switching colors. Feel free to cancel when you are good to go. TOMreverse120:
Backs out the filmament -- great for MK6 and MK7 1.75mm filament. You might find you need to help a tiny bit at the beginning (particularly w MK7) -- but resist the impulse to tug it out. Let the filament exit naturally so you leave less broken filament in the extruder. In addition, I suggest you run an Octopus v16 (here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:7900) as a calibration print. Great for checking level and x/y/z gantry quickly.

Mix and match any combination of these 8 mm and 5 mm diameter couplings. The 5 mm couplings have both round bore and D-shape profiles. Adding a spacer between the couplings increases flexibility. Any type of spacer should work (washers, nuts, standoffs, etc.) I include a spacer with an outside diameter of 36 mm x 2 mm thick. It could be scaled in the Z direction to adjust the thickness. The bolt circle diameter is 24 mm if you want to mate these to one of your own designs. It is designed to use M3 screws. NOTE: The 5 mm diameter couplings without the flat (D-shaped) have a relatively low torque capacity. 10/05/13 UPDATE:
Added another coupling. Clamp-style 3/8" diameter (Coupling_Clamp_0375in_Half.stl)

I suggest slicing all threaded parts at 0.1 mm. Non-threaded at 0.15 mm or 0.2 mm. 100% fill. PTFE tape on all threaded parts (see instructions for threaded parts on http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:110593) To make the coupling even more flexible, you could reduce the thickness of the flange. The flange is 1.6 mm thick. I use Cura for my slicer and it has a "Cut off bottom" feature that allows for this. I don't know if other slicers have a similar feature. Reducing the flange thickness by 0.4 mm makes the coupling quick a bit more flexible - although not as strong, obviously. To make the coupling less flexible, do not include a spacer between the flanges. Arrow on nut points toward other coupling (threads are tapered). I will add more detailed instructions later.

description.text: I created a front facing rectangular mount to sandwich the hotend onto the original. I also created 4 holes for 4 M3 25mm screws. They are fastened with M3 nuts, however the holes should be sized correctly to provide a very tight fit for the screws. I also added a space on top to fit a tight that screws onto the bowden PTFE tube that goes all the way down into the hotend as the black locking fastener creates too much of a wiggle with filament retracts, so the zip ties may look ugly, but they work incredibly well and there's no movement in the line. The whole thing is a very snug fit and solid as a rock once mounted to lonuf's x-gantry slider.
